The paper deals with algorithms for computing anti-chains in geometric posets, which involves both computational geometry (cs.CG) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The use of bipartite graphs and maximum matching suggests that the paper may also fall under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The problems addressed in the paper, such as computing the largest Pareto-optimal subset and largest subset of non-crossing rectangles, involve optimization and decision-making, which could be classified under artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the mention of computational complexity in the context of the independent version of the disk problem suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the field of theoretical computer science (cs.GT).
